	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Shark finning on board vessels should be totally banned, says European Parliament Fisheries Committee</h1>

			
			<h4>
												02 December 2012
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>Shark finning is the practice of cutting off shark fins, often while they are still alive, and then throwing the fish back into the sea to die. Although a ban has been in place for EU vessels since 2003, the implementing regulation still allows special permits to be issued to remove shark fins on board, provided all parts of the shark are used. At the end of 2011, the EC proposed to remove these exemptions. At its last meeting, the European Parliament Fisheries Committee supported this proposal, obliging vessels to land any sharks with their fins ‘naturally attached’. The final vote will take place in 2013 in the plenary session. </p><p>The Portuguese parliamentary rapporteur is arguing against the full deletion of these exceptions, asking rather for the scope of the exceptions to be narrowed, by issuing special fishing permits allowing the removal of shark fins on board only to freezer fishing vessels – these would include Portuguese and Spanish long-liners fishing in ACP EEZs. Several other measures are proposed by parliamentarians in order to strengthen the control of the ban on shark finning, including the obligation on captains of freezer vessels to keep detailed records of shark catches.</p><p>The European sector highlighted that such measures will result in significant losses for the sector, as shark fins and shark meat are destined to different markets, and keeping fins attached on board is likely to increase the difficulties of processing these different products once frozen. Moreover, they argue, this will not prevent ‘the rest of the fleet dedicated to catching sharks in the world, representing 93% of total shark catches, from continuing performing the finning practice’.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>European Parliament, ‘Ban shark finning on board vessels, says Fisheries Committee’, press release, 20 September 2012</p><p>
<a href="http://www.europarl.europa.eu/sides/getDoc.do?pubRef=-%2f%2fEP%2f%2fTEXT%2bIM-PRESS%2b20120917IPR51515%2b0%2bDOC%2bXML%2bV0%2f%2fEN&amp;language=EN" target="_self">http://www.europarl.europa.eu/sides/getDoc.do?pubRef=-%2f%2fEP%2f%2fTEXT...</a></p><p>Fish Information &amp; Services<i>,</i> ‘EP decision on shark finning welcomed by the Spanish’<i>,</i> press article, 20 September 2012</p><p>
<a href="http://www.fis.com/fis/worldnews/worldnews.asp?l=e&amp;country=0&amp;special=&amp;monthyear=&amp;day=&amp;id=55535&amp;ndb=1&amp;df=0" target="_self">http://www.fis.com/fis/worldnews/worldnews.asp?l=e&amp;country=0&amp;spe...</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>In October 2012, in the context of the renewal of the EU–Madagascar FPA protocol, important measures to protect and manage sharks were introduced into the FPA, allowing EU (Spanish and Portuguese) long-liners fishing in the Indian Ocean to catch only 200 tonnes of shark a year in Malagasy waters, reinforcing data collection and control for shark catches. If adopted by the Parliament, this new legislation will reduce the likelihood of these vessels cutting shark fins on board. It is also likely to improve the environmental impacts of tuna long-liner fleets involved in tuna FPAs with ACP countries. Such measures should be adequately reflected in future FPAs.</p>
		</div>
		
